    ]
  },
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'FAQPage',
    mainEntity: [
      { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is the difference between GCF and LCM?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The Greatest Common Factor (GCF) is the largest number that divides evenly into two or more numbers. The Least Common Multiple (LCM) is the smallest number that is a multiple of two or more numbers. For example, the GCF of 12 and 18 is 6, while the LCM is 36. The GCF is used to simplify fractions, and the LCM is used to find common denominators.' } },
      { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How do you find the LCM using prime factorization?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'To find the LCM using prime factorization, factor each number into primes, then take the highest power of each prime that appears in any of the factorizations and multiply them together. For example, 12 = 2 squared times 3 and 18 = 2 times 3 squared. The LCM takes the highest power of each prime: 2 squared times 3 squared = 4 times 9 = 36.' } },
      { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is the relationship between GCF and LCM of two numbers?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'For any two positive integers a and b, the product of their GCF and LCM equals the product of the two numbers: GCF(a, b) times LCM(a, b) = a times b. This relationship provides a quick way to find the LCM if you already know the GCF: LCM = (a times b) / GCF. For example, GCF(12, 18) = 6 and LCM(12, 18) = (12 times 18) / 6 = 36.' } },
    ],
  },
];
